  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis â€” jobsquare\n\n**Current state: zero test files exist anywhere in the repo.** No `tests/` directory, no `pytest` in `requirements.txt`, no CI test step (only `.github/` exists but wasn't inspected for a workflow â€” worth checking separately). Everything below is a gap. I've prioritized by correctness risk: dedup/state logic first, then parsing, then integration/network, then CLI glue.\n\nRecommend adding `pytest`, `pytest-asyncio`, and `respx` (httpx mocking) to `requirements.txt` / a new `requirements-dev.txt`.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` â€” highest priority (dedup correctness depends on this)\n\n**Untested:** `parse_posted_at`, `Job.key`, `Job.posted_dt`, `Job.content_hash`, `Job.to_row`\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- `parse_posted_at`: empty string, `None`-ish, negative epoch, exactly-1e12 boundary (ms vs s ambiguity), malformed ISO string, ISO with `Z` suffix, ISO without tz, garbage text (Workday's \"Posted 3 Days Ago\" â€” currently returns `None`, silently dropped by filters' cutoff logic since `dt is None` short-circuits).\n- `content_hash`: verify it's stable across runs (same inputs â†’ same hash) and changes when `title`/`location`/`url`/`department` change, but *not* when `posted_at`/`salary_range` change (per the docstring's contract) â€” this is exactly the kind of implicit contract a test should pin down.\n- `key`: verify stability across a title/location edit (survives), and difference across `source`/`company`/`external_id`.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"raw,expected\", [\n    (\"\", None),\n    (\"1643241332430\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 15, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # ms epoch\n    (\"1643241332\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 15, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),     # s epoch\n    (\"999999999999\", datetime(2001, 9, 9, 1, 46, 39, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),      # just under 1e12 -> seconds\n    (\"1000000000000\", datetime(1970, 1, 12, 13, 46, 40, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),   # exactly 1e12 -> ms\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00Z\", datetime(2024, 1, 15, 10, 0, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00\", datetime(2024, 1, 15, 10, 0, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # naive -> assume UTC\n    (\"Posted 3 Days Ago\", None),   # Workday prose, unparseable\n    (\"not a date\", None),\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at(raw, expected):\n    assert parse_posted_at(raw) == expected\n\n\ndef test_job_key_survives_title_edit():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\", url=\"u\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Senior Engineer\", url=\"u2\")\n    assert j1.key == j2.key\n\n\ndef test_content_hash_changes_on_material_field_but_not_posted_at():\n    base = dict(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", url=\"u\", location=\"NYC\")\n    j1 = Job(**base, title=\"Engineer\", posted_at=\"2024-01-01\")\n    j2 = Job(**base, title=\"Engineer\", posted_at=\"2024-06-01\")   # posted_at changed only\n    j3 = Job(**base, title=\"Senior Engineer\", posted_at=\"2024-01-01\")  # title changed\n    assert j1.content_hash == j2.content_hash\n    assert j1.content_hash != j3.content_hash\n\n\ndef test_to_row_excludes_raw_includes_key_and_hash():\n    j = Job(source=\"lever\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"X\", url=\"u\", raw={\"secret\": 1})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == j.key\n    assert row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `filters.py`\n\n**Untested:** `_compile`, `match`, `filter_jobs`\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- Word-boundary regex behavior: `include=[\"go\"]` shouldn't match \"Google\" or \"Django\" (currently uses `\\b` so should be safe â€” a test should confirm this, since it's a common regex bug).\n- `exclude` takes precedence over `include` even if a job matches both.\n- `locations` is substring/case-insensitive match, not exact â€” confirm `\"NYC\"` matches `\"New York City, NYC\"`.\n- `cutoff`: job with unparseable `posted_at` is **kept** (not dropped) â€” this is a deliberate but non-obvious behavior per the comment; needs a regression test.\n- `max_age_days` as a string vs int/float in `rules` (config comes from YAML, could be either).\n- Empty `rules` dict (all filters off) â†’ passthrough.\n\n```python\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef _job(**kw):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\",\n                url=\"u\", location=\"New York City, NY\", department=\"Eng\", **kw)\n\ndef test_include_uses_word_boundary_not_substring():\n    j = _job(title=\"Software Engineer, Django\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"go\"]) is False   # must not match inside \"Django\"\n\ndef test_exclude_overrides_include():\n    j = _job(title=\"Senior Staff Engineer\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"engineer\"], exclude=[\"staff\"]) is False\n\ndef test_location_filter_is_case_insensitive_substring():\n    j = _job(location=\"Remote - New York City, NYC\")\n    assert match(j, locations=[\"nyc\"]) is True\n\ndef test_cutoff_keeps_jobs_with_unparseable_posted_at():\n    j = _job(posted_at=\"Posted 3 Days Ago\")   # Workday-style, unparseable\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is True\n\ndef test_cutoff_drops_stale_confirmed_dates():\n    old = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat()\n    j = _job(posted_at=old)\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is False\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_max_age_days_as_string_from_yaml():\n    old = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat()\n    jobs = [_job(posted_at=old)]\n    assert filter_jobs(jobs, {\"max_age_days\": \"7\"}) == []\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_empty_rules_passthrough():\n    jobs = [_job()]\n    assert filter_jobs(jobs, {}) == jobs\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `store.py` â€” core dedup logic, no integration test exists at all\n\n**Untested:** `Store.__init__`/schema creation, `_migrate` (additive column), `diff` (new/changed/unchanged branches), `get_meta`/`set_meta` (insert + upsert), `added_since` (ordering, boundary), `count`.\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- `diff` called twice with identical jobs â†’ second call returns `([], [])`, only `last_seen` updates.\n- `diff` with a job whose material fields changed â†’ lands in `changed`, `content_hash` updated in DB.\n- `_migrate`: opening a pre-existing DB file that lacks `salary_range` column (simulate by creating table without it, then reopening with `Store`).\n- `added_since` strict `>` boundary â€” a row with `first_seen == ts` must be excluded.\n- `set_meta` upsert path â€” set twice, confirm second value wins, no duplicate row.\n- Context manager (`__enter__`/`__exit__`) actually closes the connection.\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\nimport pytest\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\ndef _job(ext_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\", **kw):\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=ext_id, title=title, url=\"u\", **kw)\n\ndef test_diff_first_seen_is_new(store):\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert len(new) == 1 and changed == []\n\ndef test_diff_unchanged_second_run_produces_no_new_or_changed(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert new == [] and changed == []\n\ndef test_diff_material_change_lands_in_changed(store):\n    store.diff([_job(title=\"Engineer\")])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job(title=\"Senior Engineer\")])\n    assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n\ndef test_added_since_excludes_equal_timestamp(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    row = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()\n    assert store.added_since(row[\"first_seen\"]) == []\n\ndef test_set_meta_upsert_overwrites(store):\n    store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"a\")\n    store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"b\")\n    assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") == \"b\"\n    assert store.conn.execute(\"SELECT COUNT(*) FROM meta\").fetchone()[0] == 1\n\ndef test_migrate_adds_salary_range_to_legacy_db(tmp_path):\n    path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n    conn.executescript(\"\"\"\n        CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n          external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n          employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, content_hash TEXT,\n          first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT);\n        CREATE TABLE meta (k TEXT PRIMARY KEY, v TEXT NOT NULL);\n    \"\"\")\n    conn.commit(); conn.close()\n    with Store(path) as s:\n        cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n        assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `notify.py`\n\n**Untested:** every notifier's env-var gating, `_sms_body` truncation, `dispatch`'s per-notifier exception isolation.\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- Each of `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_email`/`notify_sms`: no-op when the required env var(s) are unset, no-op when `new`/`changed` are both empty even if env vars *are* set (avoid noisy pings on empty diffs).\n- `notify_sms`: partial env vars set (3 of 4) â†’ no-op, not a crash.\n- `_sms_body`: truncation at `limit`, \"+N more\" line, and ASCII-only content (no bullet `â€˘`/ellipsis â€” GSM-only requirement called out in the comment).\n- `dispatch`: one notifier raising must not prevent the others from running â€” this is the most important gap since it's explicit resilience behavior.\n\n```python\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import Mock\nimport notify\nfrom models import Job\n\ndef _job(title=\"Engineer\", company=\"Acme\"):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=company, external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"https://x\")\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_without_env(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    post = Mock()\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", post)\n    notify.notify_slack([_job()], [])\n    post.assert_not_called()\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_no_diff(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks/x\")\n    post = Mock()\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", post)\n    notify.notify_slack([], [])\n    post.assert_not_called()\n\ndef test_notify_sms_requires_all_four_env_vars(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"tok\")\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"TWILIO_FROM\", raising=False)\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"TWILIO_TO\", raising=False)\n    post = Mock()\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", post)\n    notify.notify_sms([_job()], [])\n    post.assert_not_called()\n\ndef test_sms_body_truncates_and_counts_remainder():\n    jobs = [_job(title=f\"Role {i}\") for i in range(10)]\n    body = notify._sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert \"+2 more\" in body\n    assert body.count(\"Role\") == 8\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_notifier_failures(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"smtp down\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(notify, \"NOTIFIERS\", [boom, notify.notify_console])\n    notify.dispatch([_job()], [])\n    out = capsys.readouterr().out\n    assert \"notifier boom failed\" in out\n    assert \"NEW listing\" in out   # console notifier still ran\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `pipeline.py`\n\n**Untested:** `load_config` (defaults, missing keys), `run` (dry_run branch, normal branch), `run_sync`.\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- `load_config`: minimal YAML with only `sources:` set still gets `filters={}`, `db=\"jobs.db\"`, `concurrency=8` defaults.\n- `run(dry_run=True)`: must **not** touch the `Store` at all (currently instantiated only in the `else` branch â€” a regression here would start writing dedup state during dry runs).\n- `run`: return dict shape (`matched`/`new`/`changed`) under normal + dry-run paths.\n- These need `fetch_all`, `filter_jobs`, `Store`, `dispatch` mocked/monkeypatched â€” this is really an integration test of the orchestration wiring.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nimport yaml\nimport pipeline\nfrom models import Job\n\ndef test_load_config_applies_defaults(tmp_path):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(yaml.dump({\"sources\": [{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"acme\"}]}))\n    cfg = pipeline.load_config(cfg_path)\n    assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {}\n    assert cfg[\"db\"] == \"jobs.db\"\n    assert cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_dry_run_never_touches_store(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(yaml.dump({\"sources\": []}))\n\n    async def fake_fetch_all(sources, concurrency): \n        return [Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")]\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"fetch_all\", fake_fetch_all)\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"filter_jobs\", lambda jobs, rules: jobs)\n\n    class ExplodingStore:\n        def __init__(self, *a, **k): raise AssertionError(\"Store must not open during dry_run\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"Store\", ExplodingStore)\n\n    result = await pipeline.run(cfg_path, dry_run=True)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. `fetchers.py` â€” largest file, most untested surface area\n\n**Untested `parse_*` functions (pure, easiest to test, currently 0 coverage):** `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever` (+`_lever_salary`), `parse_ashby` (+`_ashby_salary`), `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`, `parse_google` (+`_extract_ds1`, `_ds1_posted_at`), `parse_deshaw`, `parse_twosigma`, `parse_optiver`, `parse_meta`, `parse_microsoft`, `parse_netflix`, `parse_amazon` (+`_amazon_posted_at`).\n\n**Edge cases per parser (representative, not exhaustive):**\n- Missing/`None` optional fields (location dict absent, department missing) â€” most parsers use `.get(...) or {}` chains that should degrade gracefully, not crash.\n- `parse_workable`: location as dict vs flat string â€” both branches need coverage.\n- `parse_recruitee`: location as flat string vs assembled from city/country â€” both branches.\n- `_lever_salary`: both `min`+`max` present, only one present, neither (falls back to `salaryDescriptionPlain`), numeric vs string min/max (the `fmt` lambda branches on type).\n- `_amazon_posted_at`: well-formed \"June 26, 2026\", malformed string, unknown month name â†’ must return `\"\"` not raise.\n- `_extract_ds1`: primary regex match, fallback regex match, no match at all (empty page) â€” three branches, currently all uncovered. Also invalid JSON in the matched blob â†’ `json.JSONDecodeError` caught, returns `[]`.\n- `_ds1_posted_at`: prefers index 12 over 13/14; missing/short array; falsy cell.\n- `parse_deshaw`/`parse_twosigma`: dedup via `seen` set (twosigma renders each role 3x â€” needs a fixture with duplicates to confirm the dedup actually collapses them), missing optional fields (no `mloc`/`mhref` match), HTML entity unescaping.\n- `parse_meta`: duplicate ids across the raw list dedup via `seen`; missing `id` skipped entirely.\n- `parse_microsoft`/`parse_netflix`: missing timestamp â†’ empty `posted_at` (no crash on `datetime.fromtimestamp(None,...)`).\n\n**Untested async/network layer (needs `respx` or a fake `httpx.AsyncClient` transport):**\n- `_request`: retries on 429/500/502/503/504, does **not** retry on 4xx (e.g. 404), gives up after `retries` attempts and raises `RuntimeError`, succeeds on a later attempt after failures.\n- `fetch_workday`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`: pagination loop termination â€” stops when a page returns no *fresh* ids (dedup-driven stop), stops at `max_pages` safety cap, stops when `total`/`offset` condition met (Workday).\n- `fetch_meta`: token-scraping regexes against a synthetic careers-page HTML fixture; `for (;;);` JSON prefix stripping; `data.get(\"errors\")` â†’ raises `RuntimeError` surfacing the GraphQL error message (this is a documented \"doc_id rotated\" failure mode per your [[quant-hft-ats-resolution]]-adjacent memory on ATS resolution â€” worth a dedicated regression test since it's a known recurring break point).\n- `fetch_source`: unknown `ats` key raises `ValueError` listing known ATS names.\n- `fetch_all`: one source's fetcher raising is caught and logged, doesn't fail the whole run (mirrors the `dispatch` resilience test above); concurrency semaphore actually caps in-flight requests; client is closed when `fetch_all` owns it, left open when caller supplied one.\n\n```python\nimport json\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nimport respx\nfrom fetchers import (parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_workable, parse_recruitee,\n                       _extract_ds1, _ds1_posted_at, _amazon_posted_at, parse_meta,\n                       fetch_source, fetch_all, _request)\n\n# --- pure parser edge cases ---\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"j,expected\", [\n    ({\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"}}, \"USD 100,000â€“150,000\"),\n    ({\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000}}, \"\"),  # only one bound -> falls through to description\n    ({\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}, \"Competitive\"),\n    ({}, \"\"),\n])\ndef test_lever_salary_variants(j, expected):\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == expected\n\ndef test_parse_workable_location_as_dict_vs_flat():\n    data_dict = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"T\", \"location\": {\"location_str\": \"NYC\"}}]}\n    data_flat = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 2, \"title\": \"T\", \"city\": \"SF\", \"country\": \"US\"}]}\n    assert parse_workable(\"c\", data_dict)[0].location == \"NYC\"\n    assert parse_workable(\"c\", data_flat)[0].location == \"SF, US\"\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_no_match_returns_empty():\n    assert _extract_ds1(\"<html>nothing here</html>\") == []\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_invalid_json_returns_empty():\n    html = \"key: 'ds:1', data:[not valid json] , sideChannel\"\n    assert _extract_ds1(html) == []\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"month_str,expected_prefix\", [\n    (\"June 26, 2026\", \"2026-06-26\"),\n    (\"garbage\", \"\"),\n    (\"Fooember 5, 2024\", \"\"),   # unknown month name -> KeyError caught\n])\ndef test_amazon_posted_at(month_str, expected_prefix):\n    result = _amazon_posted_at(month_str)\n    assert result.startswith(expected_prefix) if expected_prefix else result == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_meta_dedupes_by_id():\n    results = [{\"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"A\"}, {\"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"A dup\"}, {\"id\": \"2\", \"title\": \"B\"}]\n    jobs = parse_meta(\"meta\", results)\n    assert [j.external_id for j in jobs] == [\"1\", \"2\"]\n\n# --- network layer ---\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_request_retries_on_503_then_succeeds():\n    route = respx.get(\"https://example.com/x\")\n    route.side_effect = [httpx.Response(503), httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})]\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        r = await _request(client, \"https://example.com/x\", retries=3)\n    assert r.status_code == 200\n    assert route.call_count == 2\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_request_does_not_retry_on_404():\n    respx.get(\"https://example.com/x\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(404))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://example.com/x\", retries=3)\n    assert respx.calls.call_count == 1\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises():\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n            await fetch_source(client, {\"ats\": \"bogus\"})\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_isolates_one_source_failure(monkeypatch):\n    import fetchers\n    async def boom(client, source): raise RuntimeError(\"network down\")\n    async def ok(client, source): return [Mock()]\n    monkeypatch.setitem(fetchers.FETCHERS, \"greenhouse\", boom)\n    monkeypatch.setitem(fetchers.FETCHERS, \"lever\", ok)\n    jobs = await fetch_all([{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"x\"},\n                            {\"ats\": \"lever\", \"company\": \"y\"}])\n    assert len(jobs) == 1   # one source failed, the other's result survived\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py`\n\n**Untested:** `cmd_db_new` (watermark truncation logic, first-run window), `cmd_db_mark` (validation), `_normalize_ats`, `_chrome_bin` (discovery order), `run_claude`/`main` (arg routing).\n\n**Edge cases missed â€” these are the subtlest, highest-value gaps in the whole codebase:**\n- `cmd_db_new`'s truncation logic: the comment explains it truncates only at `first_seen` group boundaries (never splits a batch sharing one timestamp). This needs a test with rows spanning 3 distinct `first_seen` timestamps where the limit falls mid-group â€” assert the whole group is excluded, `truncated=True`, and `watermark` is the *last complete* group's timestamp, not a partial one.\n- `cmd_db_new` first-run (`marker is None`): `since` computed from `--since-days`, `first_run=True` in output.\n- `cmd_db_mark`: rejects a non-ISO watermark string (returns 2, doesn't write), accepts `--now`, requires either `watermark` or `--now` (returns 2 if neither).\n- `_normalize_ats`: replacements apply inside body text but **not** inside tags/`<style>`/`<script>` â€” needs a fixture HTML with an em-dash inside a tag attribute and inside `<style>` to confirm it's left untouched, plus one in visible text that IS replaced. `counts` dict correctly tallies occurrences per rule label.\n- `_chrome_bin`: `CHROME_PATH` env var takes precedence when it exists; falls back through `shutil.which` candidates; falls back to hardcoded app paths; exits via `sys.exit` when nothing found (test via `monkeypatch` faking `shutil.which` to return `None` and `Path.exists` to return `False`).\n- `main`/argv routing: `db-new`/`db-mark`/`pdf-render` subcommands dispatch correctly; bare `agent.py` â†’ `interactive=True`; `agent.py scan` â†’ non-interactive with `mode_words=[\"scan\"]`; `agent.py scan -i` â†’ interactive; mode words correctly stop at the first flag-like token, rest passed through as `extra`.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nimport agent\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_skips_style_and_tag_but_replaces_body_text():\n    html = '<style>content: \"\\u2014\";</style><p title=\"\\u2014\">He said \\u2014 hi</p>'\n    out, counts = agent._normalize_ats(html)\n    assert 'content: \"\\u2014\"' in out          # inside <style>, untouched\n    assert 'title=\"\\u2014\"' in out              # inside a tag attribute, untouched\n    assert \"He said - hi\" in out                # body text, replaced\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n\ndef test_cmd_db_mark_rejects_non_iso(capsys):\n    rc = agent.cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-timestamp\"])\n    assert rc == 2\n    assert \"not an ISO timestamp\" in capsys.readouterr().err\n\ndef test_cmd_db_mark_requires_watermark_or_now(capsys):\n    rc = agent.cmd_db_mark([])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_cmd_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary(tmp_path, monkeypatch, capsys):\n    from store import Store\n    from models import Job\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"sources: []\\ndb: {tmp_path / 'j.db'}\\n\")\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"j.db\") as s:\n        # simulate 3 pipeline runs -> 3 distinct first_seen groups of 2 rows each\n        for batch in range(3):\n            jobs = [Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=f\"{batch}-{i}\",\n                        title=\"T\", url=\"u\") for i in range(2)]\n            s.diff(jobs)\n    rc = agent.cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--limit\", \"3\"])  # limit falls mid-3rd-group\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    assert out[\"truncated\"] is True\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 4   # only first two complete groups kept\n```\n\n*(Note: this last test needs the three `diff()` calls to actually get distinct `first_seen` timestamps â€” the current `_now()`/`datetime.now()` calls are at second resolution, so this test will need either `monkeypatch` on `store.datetime` or a tiny real sleep between batches to avoid flakiness. Worth flagging as a design consideration: `cmd_db_new`'s correctness depends on distinguishable `first_seen` values, which is a fragile assumption for tests and possibly for tight back-to-back pipeline runs too.)*\n\n---\n\n### 8. `cli.py`\n\nThin, but still untested: `--dry-run` flag forwards correctly to `run_sync`, `--config`/`-c` default is `\"sources.yaml\"`.\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import Mock\nimport cli\n\ndef test_main_forwards_dry_run_flag(monkeypatch):\n    mock_run = Mock()\n    monkeypatch.setattr(cli, \"run_sync\", mock_run)\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"sys.argv\", [\"cli.py\", \"-c\", \"custom.yaml\", \"--dry-run\"])\n    cli.main()\n    mock_run.assert_called_once_with(\"custom.yaml\", dry_run=True)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Integration-test gaps (no single-file test covers these)\n\n1. **End-to-end pipeline run** with a fake in-memory config + monkeypatched `fetch_all`/`dispatch` against a real `Store` on a `tmp_path` DB â€” verifies fetch â†’ filter â†’ diff â†’ notify wiring end to end, run twice to confirm the second run reports 0 new/changed for identical input.\n2. **`agent.py db-new` â†’ `db-mark` â†’ `db-new` cycle** â€” confirms the marker actually advances and the next `db-new` excludes previously-dumped rows (this is the core \"scan\" workflow's correctness and has zero coverage).\n3. **Config loading â†’ fetcher dispatch**: a `sources.yaml`-shaped dict routed through `fetch_all` â†’ `fetch_source` for each registered ATS type, confirming `FETCHERS` registry keys match what `sources.yaml` actually uses (a drift-detection test â€” grep `sources.yaml` for `ats:` values and assert each is in `fetchers.FETCHERS`).\n\n### Missing error-handling tests, summarized\n- `fetch_all` / `dispatch`: per-item failure isolation (both have this pattern; neither is tested).\n- `_request`: exhausted-retries â†’ `RuntimeError`, non-retryable status codes.\n- `agent.py cmd_pdf_render`: missing input file (`return 2`), Chrome binary not found, Chrome runs but produces non-PDF output (`return 1`).\n- `store.py`: none currently â€” but consider what happens if `Store` is opened on a locked/corrupt DB file (currently unhandled; not necessarily a bug, but undocumented behavior worth pinning with a test or explicitly deciding out of scope).\n\n---\n\n**Suggested minimum viable first PR:** `models.py` + `filters.py` + `store.py` tests (pure logic, no mocking needed beyond `tmp_path`) â€” this covers the dedup/filtering core that everything else depends on, with the highest bug-catching value for the least setup cost. Fetchers/notify tests need `respx`/`monkeypatch` scaffolding and can follow.\n",
